history.content: <md>If there is a graduate ML course that an undergraduate can get into, CS285 is the most likely one. It is much larger and easier to get into compared to 288, 280, or 294's. It is definitely possible given that you have been a collaborator and have internships, you just need to add all of that into the google doc to get into the class. If you have another professor to vouch for you, it would make your case even better. The B in 189 hurts a lot tho, but your resume might be able for you to get in.</md>

children.subject: <md>Professor Levine's requirement is that you have only _taken_ CS 189. There is no explicit requirement on the grade you receive in the class</md>

history.content:
I heard that CS 285 professors can be very picky about undergraduate enrollment for the course. 

I'm an undergraduate EECS minor. I already took CS 189, in which I got a B. However, I participated in a CS 285 project as an outside collaborator and have done RL internships.

Do y'all think it's possible for me to enroll in CS 285 next fall?
history.subject: How hard is it to enroll in CS 285?
